stylometry: Logical upper limit is used in Nonlinear models, more specifically Fixed-Cost Models - which is when a set cost is incurred as soon as a positive number of product is produced. The Logical upper limit is the maximum capacity of product that could be produced. The limit equation can be describes as products produced < (or equal to) products produced x 0-1 variable. The 0-1 inequality describes whther the model is telling you to produce 0 or 1 of the products. the Logical upper limit makes this equation =1 if products will be produced. It also makes sure the company accounts for fixed costs in all their production, and that overproduction causing a loss of revenue does not occur.
